SIMPLE: orthodoxy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Orthodoxy
<hw>Or"tho*dox`y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/: cf. F.
<ets>orthodoxie</ets>. See <er>Orthodox</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Soundness of faith; a belief in the doctrines taught in the
Scriptures, or in some established standard of faith; -- opposed to
<ant>heterodoxy</ant> or to <ant>heresy</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Basil himself bears full and clear testimony to Gregory's
<qex>orthodoxy</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Waterland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Consonance to genuine Scriptural doctrines; -- said
of moral doctrines and beliefs; <as>as, the <ex>orthodoxy</ex> of a
creed</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>By extension, said of any generally accepted
doctrine or belief; the orthodox practice or belief.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Orthodromic</ent>⟦br⟧
